<AbstractNarration>National Science Foundation&lt;br/&gt;NSF Software Development for Cyberinfrastructure (SDCI) Program&lt;br/&gt;Office of Cyberinfrastructure&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Proposal Number: 0721939&lt;br/&gt;Principal Investigator: Michael Wilde&lt;br/&gt;Institution: University of Chicago&lt;br/&gt;Proposal Title: SDCI NMI:  Improvement of the Swift Science and Engineering Workflow Environment&lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt;Abstract&lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt;Swift is a system for Fast, Reliable, Loosely Coupled Parallel Computation. It supports applications that execute many tasks coupled by disk-resident datasets - as is common, for example, when analyzing large quantities of data or performing parameter studies or ensemble simulations. The open source Swift software combines a simple scripting language to enable the concise, high-level specifications of complex parallel computations, mappers for accessing diverse data formats in a convenient manner, and an execution engine that can manage the dispatch of many (100,000+) tasks to many (1000+) processors, whether on parallel computers, campus grids, or multi-site grids.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;</AbstractNarration>
